question_title: Will there be a successful coup in Africa or Latin America before March 1, 2026?
summary: The question asks about a successful coup in Africa or Latin America between November 28, 2025 and March 1, 2026. Key finding: Despite high recent coup activity, the Guinea-Bissau coup (Nov 26, 2025) and Madagascar coup (Oct 14, 2025) both occurred BEFORE the resolution window started. Within the window, two attempts failed (Benin Dec 7, Burkina Faso Jan 3), and the Venezuela U.S. intervention (Jan 3) is not a coup under the definition. With ~75% of the 93-day window elapsed and no qualifying successful coup, probability has declined significantly from the base rate of ~40-50% for a 3-month period. The community prediction at 53% appears high given time elapsed; I estimate ~30%.

factors.description: 75% of resolution window (70 of 93 days) has elapsed with no successful coup - this is the dominant update
High historical base rate: Africa has had ~8-10 successful coups since 2020 (~1.5-2/year), suggesting ~40-50% for a 3-month window
Recent failed attempts (Benin Dec 7, Burkina Faso Jan 3) indicate ongoing instability but also security forces are on alert
Guinea-Bissau coup occurred just 2 days before window opened (Nov 26 vs Nov 28) - 'close miss' suggests recent risk may have been 'used up' in that event
23 days remaining is still a meaningful window; coups can happen quickly when conditions align
2026 election year in many African countries (Benin April) creates potential trigger points for self-coups or military interventions
